# Docker Guidelines

## Dockerfile Best Practices

- Use official Python base images
- Multi-stage builds for smaller images
- Don't run as root user
- Copy only necessary files
- Use .dockerignore

## Example .dockerignore

```
.git
.venv
__pycache__
*.pyc
*.pyo
*.pyd
.pytest_cache
.coverage
htmlcov/
dist/
build/
*.egg-info/
```

## Docker Compose

**Important**: Do not include the `version: '3.8'` (or any version) field in `docker-compose.yaml` files. The version field was required in older Docker Compose versions but is deprecated in newer versions (v2.0+), which automatically detect the compose file format. Including it will cause warnings when running docker-compose commands.

When using docker compose, after running `make start`, output the port mappings in the following format:

```
==========================================

Services Started Successfully!

==========================================



📊 Service Ports:

  • Service 1:           http://localhost:8081

  • Service 2:           http://localhost:3000

  • Service 3:           http://localhost:5001

  • Service 4:           localhost:9092, 9093

  • Service 5:           localhost:2181



🔗 Quick Links:

  • Service 2:           http://localhost:3000

  • Service 1:           http://localhost:8081



📝 Useful Commands:

  • View logs:           make logs

  • Check status:        make status

  • Run tests:           make test-harness

  • Stop services:       make stop
```

**Note**: Adapt the service names and ports to match the actual services defined in your `docker-compose.yml` file. Extract port mappings from the docker compose configuration and format them as shown above.
